<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by darkangelx on 12-04-2001 09:37 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">this is my rc.inet1 file located in /etc/rc.d/ directory for using 2 ips on 1 nic without masquarading but I have static ips and i will be changing the ips, also my static and ip block are on different subnets


# IF YOU HAVE AN ETHERNET CONNECTION, use these lines below to configure the
 eth0 interface.

# Edit these values to set up a static IP address:
IPADDR="192.0.0.1"        # REPLACE with YOUR IP address!
NETMASK="255.255.255.102"       # REPLACE with YOUR netmask!
NETWORK="192.0.0.128"       # REPLACE with YOUR network address!
BROADCAST="192.0.0.255"     # REPLACE with YOUR broadcast address, if you
                        # have one. If not, leave blank and edit below.
GATEWAY="192.0.0.1"       # REPLACE with YOUR gateway address!
****# test eth0:0
IPADDRA="192.0.0.3"
NETMASKA="255.255.255.100"****

# To use DHCP instead of a static IP, set this value to "yes":
DHCP="no"            # Use DHCP ("yes" or "no")

# OK, time to set up the interface:
if [ "$DHCP" = "yes" ]; then # use DHCP to set everything up:
  echo "Attempting to configure eth0 by contacting a DHCP server..."
  /sbin/dhcpcd
elif [ ! "$IPADDR" = "127.0.0.1" ]; then # set up IP statically:
  # Set up the ethernet card:
  echo "Configuring eth0 as ${IPADDR}..."
  /sbin/ifconfig eth0 ${IPADDR} broadcast ${BROADCAST} netmask ${NETMASK}
****echo "Configuring eth0:0 as ${IPADDRA}..."
 /sbin/ifconfig eth0:0 ${IPADDRA} netmask ${NETMASKA}****
  # If that didn't succeed, give the system administrator some hints:
  if [ ! $? = 0 ]; then
    cat &lt;&lt; EOF

(end file here)

ok if you see **** "info"**** that is something i had to ADD to this file to get it to route

then on the windows machines
start settings control panel
specify an ip
IP 192.0.0.4 for 1 192.0.0.5 for other
subnet mask 255.255.255.100 for both
gate way tab 192.0.0.3

as you can see the gateway for the 2 windows boxes is the 2nd ip that is aliased to eth0:0 in /etc/rc.d/rc.inet1

please &lt;B&gt;NOTE&lt;/B&gt; this is for SLACKWARE not redhat or mandrake</TEXTAREA>
